Claims 7 CLAIMS What we claim is: 1. A splash controller, comprising: a housing having: an upper portion with an ingress for receiving a liquified material; a lower portion with an egress for delivering the liquified material to a conveyor; and an intermediate portion that spaces the ingress from the egress and defines an expansion chamber for the liquified material; wherein the upper portion has at least one vent opening that is separated from the ingress. 2. The splash controller of claim 1, wherein the upper portion is generally planar. 3. The splash controller of claim 1, wherein the housing is conical. 4. The splash controller of claim 3, wherein the top portion is convex. 5. The splash controller of claim 1, further comprising a diffuser that is supported by the housing above the ingress for receiving liquified material and has an open center with an exterior dimension that is greater than the ingress for receiving liquified material. 6. The splash controller of claim 1 further comprising a diffuser that is spaced from and positioned below the at least one vent. 7. A splash controller, comprising: an upper surface with an ingress having a first dimension for receiving a liquified material; a lower surface that defines an egress with a second dimension that is greater than the first dimension for delivering the liquified material to a conveyor; 

 8 an intermediate portion that is between the upper surface and the lower surface and has a third dimension that is greater than the second dimension to define an expansion chamber for the liquified material; and, at least one vent is defined on the upper surface. 8. The splash controller of claim 7 wherein the upper surface is substantially planar and has a plurality of vents. 9. The splash controller of claim 7 wherein the upper surface is convex and has a plurality of vents. 10. A splash diffusing apparatus, comprising: a housing with a receiving cavity dimensioned to receive an outlet associated with a mixing apparatus that dispenses a fluidized product to a collection vessel; a splash diffuser that is supported within the housing and defines an interior dimension that is less than the receiving cavity dimension and greater than the outlet; and, whereby, the splash diffuser intercepts splashed fluidized product and redirects the splashed fluidized product toward the collection vessel. 11. The splash diffusing apparatus of claim 10, wherein the splash diffuser includes a plurality of blades. 12. The splash diffusing apparatus of claim 11, wherein the blades are helical blades that blades are spaced around the diffuser by an arc measure of 60Â° Â± 5Â°. 13. The splash diffusing apparatus of claim 11, wherein the diffuser comprises six helical blades. 

 9 14. The splash diffusing apparatus of claim 10, further comprising a venting cap positioned above the splash diffuser. 15. The splash diffusing apparatus of claim 14, wherein the venting cap has a plurality of vanes of different diameters. 16. The splash diffusing apparatus of claim 15, wherein the plurality of vanes is angled relative to a longitudinal axis through the housing. 17. A mixing apparatus with splash controlled discharge, comprising: an outlet that delivers free falling fluidized material to a collection vessel; and a splash diffuser including: a housing with a series of helical blades that direct the fluidized material from the outlet to a collection vessel and define an escape path for entrapped gas, and, a cap that is positioned above the diffuser and around the outlet, the cap has a plurality of angled vanes that direct fluidized material toward the collection vessel while allowing entrapped gas to escape. 18. The mixing apparatus of claim 17, wherein the cap is mounted to the outlet tube. 19. The mixing apparatus of claim 17, further comprising a splash arrestor that is within the splash diffuser and has a spiral array that surrounds a section of the outlet and captures splashed fluidized material and redirects the splashed fluidized material toward the collection vessel. 20. The mixing apparatus of claim 19, wherein the spiral array of the splash arrestor extends inwardly from the housing toward the outlet by an amount that is no greater than 1 inch.
